                            <h1>
                            Joseph, the Seer
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p2" class="">Elder Neal A. Maxwell</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/neal-a-maxwell?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/neal-a-maxwell-10.jpg" alt="Neal A. Maxwell" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">03167_000_023</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p3" class="">Throughout the expanse of human history, no prophet has been scrutinized in such a sustained way, on as wide a scale, or for so long a period of time as <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a>, Jr. The communication capacity of this age and the global impact of his work have so ensured.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p4" class="">Young Joseph was told that his name would be &ldquo;both good and evil spoken of&rdquo; throughout the world. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/js-h/1.33?lang=eng#32" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">JS&mdash;H 1:33</a>.) Except from a divine source, how audacious a statement! Yet his contemporary religious leaders, then much better known than Joseph, have faded into the footnotes of history, while the work of Joseph Smith grows constantly and globally.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p5" class="">We have no hesitancy, however, in stipulating that Joseph was, by the standards of the world, &ldquo;not learned.&rdquo; Isaiah foresaw it. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/29.11-12?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 29:11&ndash;12</a>.) Joseph did not have the skilled, formal tutoring young Saul had at the feet of Gamaliel. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/22.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 22:3</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p6" class="">Emma Smith reportedly said that Joseph, at the time of the translation of the Book of Mormon, could not compose a &ldquo;well-worded letter let alone dictating a book like the Book of Mormon &hellip; [which was] marvelous to me, a marvel and a wonder, as much as to anyone else.&rdquo; (Preston Nibley, <span class="emphasis">The Witnesses of the Book of Mormon,</span> Salt Lake City: Deseret Book Co., 1968, p. 28.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p7" class="">This obscure young man apparently paused while translating and dictating to Emma&mdash;probably from the fourth chapter of 1 Nephi [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/4.title?lang=eng" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 4</a>]&mdash;concerning the &ldquo;wall of Jerusalem&rdquo;&mdash;and said, in effect, &ldquo;Emma, I didn&rsquo;t know there was a wall around Jerusalem.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p8" class="">But Joseph&rsquo;s keen mind was being awakened and expanded as the tutoring words of the Lord and of past prophets flowed through his quickened consciousness. In fact, he was the very seer foreseen anciently by the earlier Joseph in Egypt! (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/3.6-7,16-18?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 3:6&ndash;7, 16&ndash;18</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p9" class="">In a prophetic father&rsquo;s blessing given in December 1834 to Joseph Smith, Junior, Father Smith confirmed those promises given the ancient Joseph, and pronounced added blessings, including these, upon young Joseph: &ldquo;Thy God has called thee by name out of the heavens &hellip; to do a work in this generation which no other man would do as Thyself.&rdquo; The ancient Joseph &ldquo;looked after his posterity in the last days &hellip; And sought diligently to know &hellip; who would bring the word of the Lord [to them] and his eyes beheld thee, my son: [Joseph Smith, Jr.] his heart rejoiced and his soul was satisfied.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p10" class="">Young Joseph also heard his father promise, &ldquo;Thou shalt like to do the work which the Lord shall command Thee.&rdquo; (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/3.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 3:8</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p11" class="">Earlier, during the approximately ninety days of translating, Joseph was processing&mdash;and at a remarkable rate&mdash;truths and concepts of immense significance, beyond what was then his capacity. A few gems only from that treasure trove:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p12" class="">Could Joseph have been expected, for instance, to appreciate fully that, through him, would be given the only significant scriptural elaboration of one of the most fundamental and demanding declarations of Jesus?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p13" class="">&ldquo;Verily I say unto you, Except ye be converted, and become as little children, ye shall not enter into the kingdom of heaven.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/18.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 18:3</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p14" class="">Through Joseph Smith&rsquo;s translation came these stunning, defining, and sobering words about what childlike and saintly submissiveness really means:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p15" class="">&ldquo;A saint [is one who becomes] through the atonement of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a> the Lord &hellip; a child, submissive, meek, humble, patient, full of love, willing to submit to all things which the Lord seeth fit to inflict upon him, even as a child doth submit to his father.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:19</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p16" class="">Likewise, Paul wrote that since Jesus was tempted, he understood how to succor us when we are tempted. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/heb/2.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Heb. 2:18</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/heb/4.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Heb. 4:15</a>.) Yet it was through Joseph Smith that these confirming and clarifying words of Alma were given:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p17" class="">&ldquo;And [Jesus] shall go forth, suffering pains and afflictions and temptations of every kind; &hellip; he will take upon him the pains and the sicknesses of his people &hellip; that his bowels may be filled with mercy, according to the flesh, that he may know according to the flesh how to succor his people according to their infirmities.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/7.11-12?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 7:11&ndash;12</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p18" class="">Illuminated also was petitionary prayer: &ldquo;Whatsoever ye shall ask in prayer, believing, ye shall receive.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/21.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 21:22</a>.) &ldquo;Plain and precious&rdquo; and needed light was added to those words through Joseph:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p19" class="">&ldquo;And whatsoever ye shall ask the Father in my name, <span class="emphasis">which is right,</span> believing that ye shall receive, behold it shall be given unto you.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/18.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 18:20</a>; italics added.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p20" class="">&ldquo;He that asketh in the Spirit asketh according to the will of God; wherefore it is done even as he asketh.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/46.30?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 46:30</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p21" class="">Not only did confirming and clarifying truths flow through Joseph, but also rich language and deep concepts.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p22" class="">From Ammon:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p23" class="">&ldquo;How blind and impenetrable are the understandings of the children of men; for they will not seek wisdom, neither do they desire that she should rule over them!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p24" class="">&ldquo;Yea, they are as a wild flock which fleeth from the shepherd, and scattereth, and are driven.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/8.20-21?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 8:20&ndash;21</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p25" class="">From Jacob:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p26" class="">&ldquo;Ye have broken the hearts of your tender wives, and lost the confidence of your children, because of your bad examples before them; &hellip; many hearts died, pierced with deep wounds.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/2.35?lang=eng#34" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 2:35</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p27" class="">From Amulek, who finally triumphed over ambivalence:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p28" class="">&ldquo;Nevertheless, I did harden my heart, for I was called many times and I would not hear; therefore I knew concerning these things, yet I would not know.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/10.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 10:6</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p29" class="">Theology and beauty combine, again and again, in the pages provided through Joseph, as when the resurrected Christ appeared in the Western Hemisphere:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p30" class="">&ldquo;And when [Jesus] had said these words, he himself also knelt upon the earth; and behold he prayed unto the Father, and the things which he prayed cannot be written. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p31" class="">&ldquo;And no tongue can speak, neither can there be written by any man, neither can the hearts of men conceive so great and marvelous things as we both saw and heard Jesus speak; and no one can conceive of the joy which filled our souls at the time we heard him pray for us unto the Father.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/17.15-17?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 17:15&ndash;17</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p32" class="">Serious study of the blessed Book of Mormon admits one to a wonder world of complexity and beauty, even in the midst of the book&rsquo;s simple, but powerful, spiritual refrain. We are given that which we most need&mdash;yet we are athirst for more!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p33" class="">Granted, whenever the words of heaven are filtered through mortal minds and tongues there is some diminution. Yet, as with Nephi of old, so it was with Joseph Smith:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p34" class="">&ldquo;If ye shall believe in Christ ye will believe in these words, for they are the words of Christ, and he hath given them unto me.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/33.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 33:10</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p35" class="">Joseph later learned to express his own thoughts inspirationally, as in his forgiving letter of 1840 to a betraying but repenting W. W. Phelps.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p36" class="">&ldquo;It is true, that we have suffered much in consequence of your behavior&mdash;the cup of gall, already full enough for mortals to drink, was indeed filled to overflowing when you turned against us. One with whom we had oft taken sweet counsel together, and enjoyed many refreshing seasons from the Lord&mdash;&lsquo;had it been an enemy, we could have borne it.&rsquo; &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p37" class="">&ldquo;However, the cup has been drunk, the will of our Father has been done, and we are yet alive, for which we thank the Lord. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p38" class="">&ldquo;I shall be happy once again to &hellip; rejoice over the returning prodigal. &hellip;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p39" class="">&ldquo;&lsquo;Come on, dear brother, since the war is past, For friends at first, are friends again at last.&rsquo;&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">History of the Church,</span> 4:163&ndash;64.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p40" class="">Was Joseph imperfect like other prophets? Of course! Surely, Joseph could identify with these words of an ancient prophet, which he translated:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p41" class="">&ldquo;Condemn me not because of mine imperfection, neither my father, because of his imperfection, &hellip; but rather give thanks unto God that he hath made manifest unto you our imperfections, that ye may learn to be more wise than we have been.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/morm/9.31?lang=eng#30" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Morm. 9:31</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/67.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 67:5</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p42" class="">Joseph, who translated the instructive words &ldquo;there is an opposition in all things&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/2.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 2:11</a>), came to understand, by experience, that the calisthenics of spiritual growth involve isometrics, the pitting of the emerging self against the stern resistance of the old self.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p43" class="">Did Joseph experience the same anxieties in carrying out his mission as did other prophets? Indeed! Joseph could understand with what feelings a weary and beset Paul wrote:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p44" class="">&ldquo;For, when we were come into Macedonia, our flesh had no rest, but we were troubled on every side; without were fightings, within were fears.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-cor/7.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Cor. 7:5</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-cor/4.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Cor. 4:8</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p45" class="">Was Joseph unjustly accused as were other prophets? Yes! Even unto this very day fragments of fact are flung at his memory. Paul was accused of being mad and deranged. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/26.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 26:24</a>.) Even Jesus himself was accused of being a winebibber, of being possessed of a devil, and of being mad. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/11.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 11:19</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/10.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 10:20</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p46" class="">Yet, in the midst of all these things, as promised, Joseph loved the work to which he had been called. And he loved his associates! In giving individual assignments to the Twelve, we see his love and humor tenderly intertwined:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p47" class="">&ldquo;John Taylor, I believe you can do more good in the editorial department than preaching. You can write for thousands to read; while you can <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/library/display/0,4945,8057-1-4424-1,00.html">preach</a> to but a few at a time. We have no one else we can trust the paper with, and hardly with you, for you suffer the paper to come out with so many mistakes.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">History of the Church,</span> 5:367.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p48" class="">Joseph was filled with mercy as evidenced in the healing of the many fevered sick on the banks of a river, and where his hands could not go, Joseph sent a healing handkerchief! (See <span class="emphasis">History of the Church,</span> 4:3&ndash;5.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p49" class="">He sorrowed over his loss of a newborn child and was given permission to care for a neighbor&rsquo;s child during the day, then return the baby to her mother at night. An older sister of the baby, Margarette McIntire, later reported:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p50" class="">&ldquo;One evening he did not come [home] with [the child] at the usual time, and mother went down to the Mansion to see what was the matter, and there sat the Prophet with the baby wrapped up in a little silk quilt. He was trotting it on his knee, and singing to it to get it quiet before starting out.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Ensign,</span> Jan. 1971, pp. 36&ndash;37.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p51" class="">Was Joseph a leader-servant? Demonstrably! A girl and her brother were struggling in the deep mud on their way to school. The Prophet Joseph &ldquo;stooped down and cleaned the mud from our little heavy-laden shoes, took his handkerchief from his pocket, and wiped our tear-stained faces. He spoke kind and cheering words to us, and sent us on our way to school rejoicing.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Juvenile Instructor,</span> 15 Jan. 1892, p. 67.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p52" class="">In fleeing with Joseph from a mob, a young man reported, &ldquo;sickness and fright had robbed me of my strength. Joseph had to decide whether to leave me to be captured by the mob, or endanger himself by rendering aid. Choosing the latter course, he lifted me upon his broad shoulders and bore me with occasional rest through the swamp and darkness. Several hours later we emerged upon the only road and soon reached safety. Joseph&rsquo;s herculean strength permitted him to [save] my life.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">New Era,</span> Dec. 1973, p. 19.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p53" class="">A victim of intolerance, Joseph Smith was deeply offended when a Catholic convent was burned in New England, saying, &ldquo;Yes, in sight of the very spot where the fire of American Independence was first kindled.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">History of the Church,</span> 2:465.) Maligned, even today, Joseph once declared, &ldquo;I am just as ready to die in defending the rights of a Presbyterian, a Baptist, or &hellip; any other denomination.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">History of the Church,</span> 5:498.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p54" class="">While most mortals misunderstand the significance of Joseph&rsquo;s ministry, the adversary surely did not!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p55" class="">Unsurprisingly, Joseph Smith, Jr., was still growing spiritually and intellectually, when he was murdered. Yet, Joseph lived long enough to &ldquo;lay out the plan of all the work which God has given you to do&rdquo; as promised in the blessing from his dying father in 1840. Now the ends of the earth inquire after his name. No wonder an admiring but dying Brigham Young&rsquo;s last words were &ldquo;Joseph, Joseph, Joseph!&rdquo; (Joseph Fielding Smith, <span class="emphasis">Essentials in Church History,</span> 24th ed., Salt Lake City: Deseret Book Co., 1971, p. 459.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p56" class="">Thus, those who revile Joseph Smith will not change Joseph&rsquo;s status with the Lord (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/3.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 3:8</a>)&mdash;merely their own! Instead&mdash;as was promised Joseph in an 1834 father&rsquo;s blessing:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p57" class="">&ldquo;Thousands and tens of thousands shall come to a knowledge of the truth, through thy ministry, and thou shalt rejoice with Them in the Celestial Kingdom; [and] thou shalt stand on Mount Zion when the tribes of Jacob come shouting from the north, and with thy brethren, the Sons of Ephraim, crown them in the name of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p58" class="">Some may seek to explain Joseph merely by attaching to him the generous adjective <span class="emphasis">remarkable.</span> Joseph was remarkable, but, much more importantly, he was instrumental!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p59" class="">Even now, one hears faintly the distant but approaching drum roll of history building towards a crescendo of mortal recognition when all shall see &ldquo;things as they really are.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/4.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 4:13</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p60" class="">Meanwhile, the ancient records which a young Joseph translated will be with us &ldquo;from generation to generation as long as the earth shall stand.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/25.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 25:22</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/5.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 5:10</a>.) These records defined a seer as one who can translate ancient records, is a revelator, and knows of things past and future. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/8.13-17?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 8:13&ndash;17</a>.) Such a seer, wrote Ammon, is greater than a prophet! (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/8.15-17?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 8:15&ndash;17</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p61" class="">Therefore, brothers and sisters, I have no hesitancy&mdash;only gladness&mdash;in declaring my everlasting admiration for Joseph, the Seer! I thank the Father for providing such a seer! I thank my Lord and Savior, Jesus Christ, for calling, directing, and tutoring Joseph!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1983/11/joseph-the-seer.p62" class="">Humbly, I give apostolic &ldquo;praise to the man who communed with Jehovah,&rdquo; in the name of Jesus Christ, amen!</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
